# TMvault on-prem deployment — Taylor Morrison
# Target: 5,000 users / 260 TiB / single tenant
# Copy this to `.env`, fill in the angle-bracket placeholders, deploy.
#
# Sizing assumptions (revise if Taylor's profile differs):
#   - 5,000 mailboxes + 5,000 OneDrives + 5,000 Teams identities
#   - 260 TiB total OneDrive/SharePoint footprint (~52 GB/user avg)
#   - ~50M total files (assuming ~5 MB average); ~10k files/user
#   - ~100M Graph metadata calls for first sync
#   - Daily change rate ~1-3% (typical enterprise)
#
# First-sync wall-time projection (with this config):
#   - 12 apps × ~5 RPS sustained = 60 RPS metadata throughput
#   - 100M calls / 60 RPS ≈ 20 days metadata, runs parallel to bytes
#   - 260 TiB at 10 Gbps ≈ 60 hours bytes; at 25 Gbps ExpressRoute ≈ 24h
#   - Combined wall: ~14-21 days first sync, depending on network pipe
#   - After first sync: daily incrementals ~3-6 hours (1-3% change rate)


# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 1) AZURE AD APP REGISTRATIONS (12 apps in Taylor's tenant)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Each app: Entra ID → App registrations → New registration
#   - Name: TMvault-Backup-01 ... TMvault-Backup-12
#   - Application permissions (NOT delegated): Mail.Read, Mail.ReadBasic.All,
#     Files.Read.All, Sites.Read.All, Chat.Read.All, ChannelMessage.Read.All,
#     Calendars.Read, Contacts.Read, User.Read.All, Group.Read.All,
#     Directory.Read.All, DeviceManagementManagedDevices.Read.All
#   - Grant admin consent in Taylor's tenant for ALL 12 apps
#   - Generate a client secret for each, copy below
#
# Why 12 apps in own tenant is fine for enterprise: customers routinely
# register dozens of integration apps in their own tenant (every SaaS
# vendor adds one). 12 backup-specific apps in your own tenant for
# legitimate backup of your own data is a normal enterprise IT pattern.
# Microsoft's "anti-throttling-via-many-apps" concern is about VENDORS
# spinning up apps in VENDOR tenant to abuse per-customer quotas — not
# customers running their own backup tooling.

APP_1_CLIENT_ID=<app-1-client-id>
APP_1_CLIENT_SECRET=<app-1-secret>
APP_1_TENANT_ID=<taylor-tenant-id>

APP_2_CLIENT_ID=<app-2-client-id>
APP_2_CLIENT_SECRET=<app-2-secret>
APP_2_TENANT_ID=<taylor-tenant-id>

APP_3_CLIENT_ID=<app-3-client-id>
APP_3_CLIENT_SECRET=<app-3-secret>
APP_3_TENANT_ID=<taylor-tenant-id>

APP_4_CLIENT_ID=<app-4-client-id>
APP_4_CLIENT_SECRET=<app-4-secret>
APP_4_TENANT_ID=<taylor-tenant-id>

APP_5_CLIENT_ID=<app-5-client-id>
APP_5_CLIENT_SECRET=<app-5-secret>
APP_5_TENANT_ID=<taylor-tenant-id>

APP_6_CLIENT_ID=<app-6-client-id>
APP_6_CLIENT_SECRET=<app-6-secret>
